Amend the European Stability Pact
The European Stability Pact, which underpins the euro by imposing constraints determining the size of budget deficits of Union members, is in danger.
Germany, the heavy-weight of the Union, has not succeeded in fulfilling its budgetary commitments to its European partners.
Furthermore, it has used its political weight to cover the early warning signal of its deficit, established by the European Commission according to the terms of the Stability Pact.
Today it is France that is playing the bad guy.
The second member of the Union, somewhat reluctant, has now also officially declared that it cannot fulfill its commitment to reduce the budget deficit, a year after the small Ireland received an official warning regarding its fiscal policies, despite its budget surpluses, and in a very severe manner.
Thus, four years after its signing, the stability pact is a real disaster.
In fact, Europe seems very affected by the discussions aiming to eliminate it, as well as those aiming to amend it.
And rightly so: the pact is poorly designed and its implementation is poorly done.
The limitation of the deficit to 3% of GDP is arbitrary and without consideration of the fact that deficits automatically increase when the economy slows down.
Assuming this fact, the architects of the pact made the situation worse by adopting two "ill-conceived" solutions.
They introduced a safety clause allowing any country to suspend its deficit limits in case of a major recession, but they defined it in such a way that any suspension is virtually impossible in practice.
Concerned that serious slowdowns might undermine the deficit ceiling, they decreed that a normal deficit was equivalent to zero deficit.
Thus, each year, each country must submit a budget forecast for the next two years demonstrating how the budget balance will be achieved in due time.
The German commitment for 2002 was made in 2001, when its economy was growing at a reasonable pace.
The unexpected slowdown prevents Germany from achieving its goals.
Finance Minister Hans Eichel reasonably decided not to worsen the situation by adopting a fiscal contractionary policy.
The Commission, seeking to position itself as the protector of the pact, wanted to issue a warning, but this decision had to be made by real politicians, the Council of Finance Ministers.
No one wanted to embarrass Germany since everyone recognized they could face the same problem in the future.
Thus, no warning was issued.
The situation in France is different.
During election periods, politicians inevitably make promises, such as reducing the tax burden.
In a country where the tax burden is significant, it is not only a matter of political intelligence but also economic intelligence, as long as budget expenditures are also reduced.
However, France is also a country where everyone benefits from certain privileges funded by the state, and as a result, budget cuts are definitely poorly perceived.
Thus, France cannot meet its objectives, and the Commission has expressed its frustration.
But France has become master of the art of defying the laws of the Union.
Political maneuvers will follow, inevitably.
Economists and cynics are not greatly surprised.
The objective of the pact, to establish a fiscal discipline within countries sharing the same currency, is entirely acceptable.
However, the loss of control over their national monetary policy, the members of the Union no longer benefit from just one macroeconomic tool: fiscal policies.
The challenge is therefore to combine long-term discipline with short-term flexibility.
Just like promising to go on a diet before a big party, this challenge is not easy to reconcile.
The stability pact is too rudimentary and technocratic: the 3% target set by Brussels bureaucrats cannot bind politicians in office.
The solution must be found elsewhere.
Fortunately, we do not have to look very far.
The monetary policy faces the same challenge.
It must stabilize long-term prices while remaining sufficiently flexible in the short term to manage economic cycles.
Over the past ten years, monetary policy experienced real success.
The recipe is the same everywhere: it suffices to delegate this policy to a competent group, the central bank, by granting it the necessary political independence and a clear and well-defined mandate.
Knowing that any misstep will have to be addressed in the future, it is up to it to exercise good judgment.
Ceci s'est révélé une des améliorations majeures dans le domaine monétaire de ces dernières années.
The same approach should work for fiscal policy.
Some fear, of course, to lose out on democracy.
It is essential to understand that fiscal policy serves two very different purposes.
The first is structural and redistributive and concerns the importance of the budget and its detailed structure, both in terms of expenditures and in terms of revenues.
Decisions regarding these issues cannot be delegated and must remain in the hands of elected governments and be subject to parliamentary approval and management
The second is macroeconomic: it involves defining the budget balance to manage fluctuation cycles.
It differs little from monetary policy and can be delegated to an independent body.
Thus, the task of Europe is clear.
Each country must regain full control over its fiscal policies but delegate its macroeconomic components, its decisions on deficits or surpluses, to an independent Fiscal Policy Committee whose long-term objective is the stabilization (or reduction, for some countries) of public debt.
To ensure the outcome, the status of such a Committee and its mandates must be subject to consensus within the Union, without any interference from Brussels, without any arbitrary regulations, without any political decision-making, but simply by relying on common sense.
